{{Quote|My friend Salak&hellip; he's not coming back. I know that now. I guess I've known it a long, long time.|Noa Briqualon|<ref name="Battle for Endor" />}}
'''Salak Weet''', also known to the [[Sanyassan/Legends|Sanyassan]] [[King/Legends|King]] [[Terak]] as '''the star traveler''', was a [[Humanoid/Legends|Humanoid]] [[Gender/Legends|male]] [[Scout/Legends|explorer]] whose [[Noa Briqualon's starship|starship]] crashed onto the [[Forest/Legends|Forest]] [[Moon/Legends|Moon]] of [[Endor/Legends|Endor]] around the [[Standard year/Legends|year]] [[26 BBY/Legends|26 BBY]]. Weet had been attempting to chart the [[Moddell sector/Legends|Moddell sector]] with his friend [[Noa Briqualon]], but a damaged [[crystal oscillator]] in their [[Starship/Legends|star cruiser]] left them stranded on Endor. After setting out to search the moon for a replacement part, Weet was taken [[Prisoner/Legends|captive]] by a group of shipwrecked [[Sanyassan Marauders]] and brought to their [[Terak's Keep|castle stronghold]]. Misunderstanding the tale he told them, the primitive Marauders believed that he had the "power of the [[Star/Legends|stars]]," a power they could take from him and use to leave the moon. Weet was in turn [[Death/Legends|killed]] by Terak, their king.

Weet's corpse hung in the [[Castle/Legends|castle's]] [[Prison/Legends|dungeon]] over the years as the Sanyassans continued to [[Hunting/Legends|hunt]] for the "power." Although Briqualon accepted that his friend would not return, Weet's father [[Jimke Weet|Jimke]] organized a massive search effort that finally bankrupted him [[22 BBY/Legends|after]] four years. Weet's fate was confirmed to Briqualon in [[3 ABY/Legends|3 ABY]], when Briqualon infiltrated the Marauders' castle to rescue his captive friend [[Cindel Towani]] and came across Weet's [[Skeleton/Legends|skeleton]]. The skeleton's presence helped Briqualon realize that Towani's own [[Crystal/Legends|crystal]] oscillator was in the castle, and, after escaping with it, he and Towani were able to leave Endor.

==Biography==
===Stranded===
{{Quote|He told us about this. He told us it was the key to all his power. A power greater than mine. Greater than Terak's.''"<br />"''But it's just a piece of a star cruiser!''"<br />"''That's right. The power of the stars! It's what Salak was searching for long ago.|Charal and Cindel Towani, speaking of a crystal oscillator|<ref name="Battle for Endor" />}}
The [[Humanoid/Legends|Humanoid]] [[Gender/Legends|male]] Salak<ref name="Battle for Endor" /> Weet lived during the final [[Standard year/Legends|years]] of the [[Galactic Republic/Legends|Galactic Republic]]. He was the son of [[Jimke Weet]], a renowned [[Kloo horn/Legends|kloo horn]] [[Musician/Legends|soloist]]. Shortly before [[26 BBY/Legends|26 BBY]],<ref name="HNN" /> the younger Weet set out to chart the [[Moddell sector/Legends|Moddell sector]] alongside his friend [[Noa Briqualon]], a [[Human/Legends|Human]] who had spent [[Standard year/Legends|years]] as a mid-level [[Scout/Legends|scout]].<ref name="Noa DB">{{DB|character|noa|Briqualon, Noa}}</ref> On the two [[Scout/Legends|explorers]]' maiden voyage, they reached the Moddell [[Sector/Legends|sector's]] [[Monsua Nebula/Legends|Monsua Nebula]], from where they broadcast a [[Transponder code/Legends|responder signal]].<ref name="HNN" /> Shortly afterward, their [[Noa Briqualon's starship|star cruiser]] crashed onto [[Endor/Legends|Endor]],<ref name="Battle for Endor" /> a [[Tree/Legends|forested]] [[Moon/Legends|moon]] that had claimed hundreds of ships throughout the [[Time/Legends|millennia]]<ref name="Castaways of Endor">{{Hyperspace|url=fans/hyperspace/source/feature20081201.html|text=Castaways of Endor|int=Castaways of Endor}}</ref> due to the presence of nearby [[Gravity/Legends|gravity]] [[Mass shadow/Legends|shadows]] and stellar debris.<ref name="Endor and the Moddell sector">{{GamerCite|9|Endor and the Moddell Sector}}</ref> A damaged [[crystal oscillator]] rendered the [[Starship/Legends|ship]] inoperable, and the explorers hid their [[Cruiser/Legends|cruiser]]<ref name="Noa DB" /> beneath a layer of [[Plant/Legends|foliage]],<ref name="Battle for Endor" /> from where they began to enact repairs. Weet eventually left<ref name="Noa DB" /> to search the moon for a replacement oscillator.<ref name="Battle for Endor" />

While wandering through the forest, Weet encountered a group of [[Sanyassan Marauders]]<ref name="Noa DB" /> who had themselves been stranded on Endor for nearly a century. The [[Sanyassan/Legends|Sanyassans]] captured Weet<ref name="Sanyassan DB">{{DB|species|marauder|Sanyassan Marauders}}</ref> and brought him to [[Terak's Keep]], the [[Castle/Legends|castle]] stronghold of their leader, [[King/Legends|King]] [[Terak]]. There, they chained Weet to the walls of the keep's [[Prison/Legends|dungeon]],<ref name="Battle for Endor" /> and he told his captors of the stranded [[Star/Legends|star]] cruiser<ref name="Sanyassan DB" /> and his [[Hunting/Legends|hunt]] for a [[Crystal/Legends|crystal]] oscillator.<ref name="Battle for Endor" /> The primitive Marauders were both desperate to leave Endor and fascinated by the "power of the stars"&mdash;their term for the ability to travel through [[Realspace/Legends|space]]<ref name="Terak DB">{{DB|character|terak|Terak}}</ref>&mdash;and Terak [[Death/Legends|killed]] Weet in an attempt to gain that power.<ref name="Battle for Endor" /> When the murder accomplished nothing, the Marauders embarked on a quest to locate Weet's ship and the great power they presumed was contained therein.<ref name="Sanyassan DB" /> Weet's corpse was left in the dungeon to rot.<ref name="Battle for Endor" />

===Legacy===
{{Quote|I know that Salek ''[sic]'' is still alive somewhere. If anyone has any information, or any of my fans are willing to donate credits to the search, please contact the Salek-Come-Home ''[sic]'' HoloNet registry.|Jimke Weet, interviewed on HoloNet News|<ref name="HNN" />}}
[[File:Salekskeleton.jpg|thumb|left|250px|Weet's skeleton hung in Terak's Keep for years after his death.]]
In 26 [[Galactic Standard Calendar|BBY]], Jimke Weet organized a massive search-and-rescue effort for his son and set up a corresponding [[Salek-Come-Home HoloNet registry|HoloNet registry]] for the receipt of information from anyone who had it. [[22 BBY/Legends|After]] four fruitless years, he was forced to file for bankruptcy and abandon his efforts. However, the elder Weet refused to give up hope, and in an interview with [[HoloNet News/Legends|HoloNet News]], he asked his fans to donate any available [[Galactic Credit Standard/Legends|credits]] to the registry in order to help revive the search.<ref name="HNN" /> Meanwhile, on Endor, Weet's body decomposed into a [[Skeleton/Legends|skeleton]] as the years passed. Although his name was known to Terak's accomplice [[Charal]], Weet was remembered by Terak as "the star traveler."<ref name="Battle for Endor" />

Briqualon continued repair work on the crashed star cruiser<ref name="Battle for Endor" /> for nearly three decades.<ref name="HNN" /><ref name="Behind the Magic" /> Although he realized that Weet would not return, he refused to admit it to himself until<ref name="Battle for Endor" /> [[3 ABY/Legends|3 ABY]]<ref name="Behind the Magic" /> when he shared his story with [[Cindel Towani]], a young shipwrecked Human girl whom he had befriended. The Marauders had [[Raid on Bright Tree Village|attacked]] an [[Ewok/Legends|Ewok]] [[Bright Tree Village/Legends|village]] and killed her entire [[Towani family|family]] before stealing the crystal oscillator from their [[Towani family star cruiser|star cruiser]], recognizing it as the power of which Weet had spoken. Towani learned of Weet's fate after later being kidnapped by the Marauders, and when Briqualon stormed Terak's Keep to rescue her, she pointed out Weet's skeleton and told Briqualon that his friend had been killed for "the power thing." Quickly realizing that she meant her family's oscillator, Briqualon snatched it from the castle; after defeating Terak in [[Battle of Endor (Ewok–Sanyassan conflict)|battle]], he used the oscillator to power his ship and leave Endor with Towani.<ref name="Battle for Endor" />

==Personality and traits==
{{Quote|My friend Salak and I&hellip; we were a couple of young fellas out to tear up the galaxy!|Noa Briqualon|<ref name="Battle for Endor" />}}
As a young man, Salak Weet was eager to set out on his charting expedition, hoping that he and Briqualon could "tear up [[The galaxy/Legends|the galaxy]]." When kidnapped by the Sanyassan Marauders, Weet revealed information to them.<ref name="Battle for Endor" /> After crashing onto Endor, he was missed by his [[Parent/Legends|father]], who openly wept to the [[Media/Legends|media]].<ref name="HNN" />

==Behind the scenes==
{{Quote|You see, it was in this Star Cruiser that I crashed to Endor many years ago. My power supply, a crystal oscillator, was shattered. I thought I could fix it but I can't. Without a new crystal oscillator, I can never hope to go home.|Noa Briqualon, leaving out any mention of Weet in ''The Ring, the Witch, and the Crystal: An Ewok Adventure''|<ref name="children's book">''[[The Ring, the Witch, and the Crystal: An Ewok Adventure]]''</ref>}}
The character of Salak was introduced in ''[[Ewoks: The Battle for Endor]]'', a [[1985]] television movie directed by [[Jim Wheat|Jim]] and [[Ken Wheat]]. Although he appears only as a long-dead skeleton, the movie's plot is driven by Salak's past actions.<ref name="Battle for Endor" /> The character was named after actor [[Wikipedia:Tom Selleck|Tom Selleck]], whom [[Wikipedia:ABC Entertainment|ABC Entertainment]] originally suggested to play the role of Noa before [[Wilford Brimley]] was cast.<ref name="Ken Wheat e-mail">{{EmailCite|email=Wookieepedia:Email/Ken Wheat|creator=[[Ken Wheat]]|date=2011-08-01}}</ref> Salak is not included in ''[[The Ring, the Witch, and the Crystal: An Ewok Adventure]]'', a truncated children's storybook adaptation of the movie written by [[Cathy East Dubowski]]&mdash;in the storybook, Briqualon tells Towani that he crashed onto Endor years before, but he makes no mention of having been with a partner. Additionally, the book does not provide a backstory to the Sanyassan Marauders' desire to leave Endor.<ref name="children's book" />

Further information on Weet's past was later revealed in the [[StarWars.com]] [[Databank (original)|Databank]]<ref name="Noa DB" /><ref name="Sanyassan DB" /><ref name="Terak DB" /> and in "Missing Starship Search Abandoned", a [[2002]] article published in [[HoloNet News Vol. 531 49|Volume 531, Issue 49]] of the [[HoloNet News (original website)|HoloNet News website]]<ref name="HNN" /> that was written by [[Pablo Hidalgo]] and [[Paul Ens]].<ref name="Credits">{{HoloNetNewsWeb||credits.html|text=Credits}}</ref> The article spells the character's name as "Salek,"<ref name="HNN" /> as does [[Warriors of Endor|another article]] included in [[Star Wars Insider 110|''Star Wars Insider'' 110]].<ref name="Warriors of Endor">{{InsiderCite|110|Warriors of Endor}}</ref> However, this spelling is contrary to the spelling of "Salak" given in the subtitles of the [[2004]] ''Ewoks: The Battle for Endor'' [[Star Wars: Ewok Adventures|DVD release]],<ref name="DVD">''[[Star Wars: Ewok Adventures]]''</ref> the Databank entries,<ref name="Noa DB" /><ref name="Sanyassan DB" /><ref name="Terak DB" /> and [[2008]]'s ''[[The Complete Star Wars Encyclopedia]]''.<ref name="CSWE">{{CSWECite|I|94|Briqualon, Noa}}</ref> Nevertheless, the two erring articles are the only sources to provide the last name of "Weet," and as such, the correctly spelled full name "Salak Weet" has never appeared in [[canon]].<ref name="HNN" />

